article.description: Adrienne Goodson scored 20 points, hitting her first seven shots, and Margo Dydek had 11 points, 13 rebounds and four blocked shots as Utah beat Houston 66-59 Friday night for a 1-0 lead in the teams' first-round playoff series.
article.headline: Starzz hold off Comets for first playoff victory

images.name: Dydek_Margo 020816 inline
images.caption: Margo Dydek and Utah look to dethrone the Los Angeles Sparks.

article.linkText: Starzz hold off Comets for first playoff victory
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Adrienne Goodson shot like it was target practice, Marie Ferdinand was a defensive pest and the Utah Starzz held on for their first-ever WNBA playoff victory. Goodson scored 20 points, hitting her first seven shots, and Margo Dydek had 11 points, 13 rebounds and four blocked shots as Utah beat Houston 66-59 Friday night for a 1-0 lead in the best-of-three first-round playoff series. Marie Ferdinand scored 12 points and, along with Jennifer Azzi, pestered perennial Houston All-Star Sheryl Swoopes into a 17-point effort on 5-of-19 shooting. "I was trying to be like a mosquito and bother her,'' Ferdinand said. "Down the stretch, we got stops and rebounds. We helped each other defensively and it gave them fits.'' The Starzz almost blew a 17-point second-half lead. Goodson's two baskets after the break gave Utah a 43-26 advantage but it didn't phase the Comets, who rallied from a franchise-record 18-point deficit to beat Seattle last month. This time, Houston switched a second-half zone. "It changed the game,'' Goodson said. "Marie and I had trouble driving to the basket.'' Using runs of 8-2 and 8-0, the Comets pulled to 59-56 on Rita Williams' 3-pointer with 4:30 to play and 61-59 on two free throws by Swoopes with 2:53 left. But the Starzz took over defensively, holding Houston scoreless the rest of the way. Azzi and Goodson each hit two free throws in the final 1:12 as Utah went 5-of-6 from the foul line to seal the win. "We knew they would make their run,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. "We withstood it and I'm proud of our team.'' The Comets couldn't offset a first-half stretch where they missed 17 straight field goals. "I don't believe I've had a team miss that many shots since I coached eighth grade basketball in Mississippi,'' said Houston coach Van Chancellor, a 38-year coaching veteran. "You can't miss 17 shots in a row and beat anybody.'' Azzi had 10 for the Starzz, who were swept by Sacramento in their first playoff trip last year. Goodson finished 8-for-13 from the field, but she was more concerned about traveling to Houston for Game 2 on Sunday. "It's about surviving their runs. Houston is a great team,'' Goodson said. "Even when they're playing bad, they're a great team. I'm not going to get too excited about this.'' The Comets won 13 straight at home over one stretch this season. "We did a good job coming back,'' Swoopes said. "If there's any one thing we can take away from this, it's that we're going back home.'' Janeth Arcain scored 10 of her 16 points after halftime, leading the comeback. Tina Thompson scored 13 points but missed a 3-pointer with a minute to go that would have pulled Houston within 63-62. The Comets held opponents to 37.5 percent shooting this season, best in the WNBA. But the Starzz seemed to make just about anything they put up in the first half, shooting 68 percent at one point. Chancellor was asked to identify Houston's first-half defensive trouble. "Guarding them all, hard to sag off of anybody,'' he said. "They can all score. They all drove to the hole. They just sliced and diced in the first half. Unbelievable. Give them credit.''

Game notes
Chancellor was assessed a technical foul early in the second half, arguing calls as the Comets faced their 17-point deficit. ... Attendance was 6,693, a disappointing showing considering Utah's three-year franchise contract is up for renewal. ... In the WNBA's six years, the Comets are 17-5 against Utah, but the Starzz have won two straight. ... Houston shot 29 percent.
